Given: e eggs f floors Find:

minimum number of attempts needed in worst case
to determine highest safe floor


Drop egg from floor k

Two cases:
1. Egg Breaks
    check below floors
    eggs reduce by 1
    Problem becomes: (e-1, k-1)
2. Egg Survives
    check upper floors
    same eggs remain
    Problem becomes: (e, f-k)

Need worst case: 1 + max(break, survive)

DP Formula

dp[e][f]=1+min
1≤k≤f (max(dp[e−1][k−1], dp[e][f−k]))


Why Binary Search Works

We compare: breakCase vs surviveCase
Case 1 breakCase > surviveCase
    egg breaking side dominates
    move downward
    high = mid - 1;
Case 2 surviveCase > breakCase
    upper floors dominate
    move upward
    low = mid + 1;

class Solution {

    // Function to find minimum number of attempts needed in
    static int[][] dp;
    // order to find the critical floor.
    static int eggDrop(int n, int k) {
        // code here
         dp = new int[n+1][k+1];
         
         for(int[] row: dp){
             Arrays.fill(row,-1);
         }
         return solve(n,k);
    }
    
    static int solve(int eggs, int floors){
        
        if(floors==0 || floors==1){
            return floors;
        }
        if(eggs==1){
            return floors;
        }
        if(dp[eggs][floors] != -1){
            return dp[eggs][floors];
        }
        int minAttempts= Integer.MAX_VALUE;
        int low =1;
        int high=floors;
        while (low <=high){
            int mid = (low+high)/2;
            int breakCase= solve(eggs-1,mid-1);
            int surviveCase = solve(eggs,floors-mid);
            
            int attempts= 1+ Math.max(breakCase,surviveCase);
            
             minAttempts= Math.min(attempts,minAttempts);
             if(breakCase> surviveCase){
                 high =mid-1;
             }else{
                 low =mid+1;
             }
        }
        return dp[eggs][floors] = minAttempts;
    }
}
